 <link>https://www.vapor.ucar.edu/gallery/hurricane-sandy/potential-vorticity-t322-isosurface-viewed-south</link>
 <description>&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-field-image-upload field-type-image field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://www.vapor.ucar.edu/sites/default/files/styles/100__wide/public/gallery/images/sandyAMSPV322T.jpg?itok=2fbrDM6W&quot; width=&quot;675&quot; height=&quot;534&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;WRF-ARW potential vorticity (PV) on the 322-K isentropic surface.  Key features include: Encirclement of Sandy inner-core by 322-K polar stratospheric PV.  Radial contraction of low-level PV ring concurrent with downward-penetration of 322-K PV prio to landfall.  Colored according to potential vorticity units (PVU). Discussed in &lt;a href=&quot;https://ams.confex.com/ams/93Annual/flvgateway.cgi/id/23249?recordingid=23249&quot;&gt;Mel Shapiro&#039;s presentation at the AMS 2013 Townhall&lt;/a&gt; &quot;A research-community perspective of the life cycle of Hurricane Sandy&quot;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
