 <title>Potential temperature at 1000 meters</title>
 <link>https://www.vapor.ucar.edu/gallery/hurricane-sandy/potential-temperature-1000-meters</link>
 <description>&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-field-image-upload field-type-image field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://www.vapor.ucar.edu/sites/default/files/styles/100__wide/public/gallery/images/sandyAMST1000.jpg?itok=_lm-Uqnl&quot; width=&quot;675&quot; height=&quot;532&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-items&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;field-item even&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;WRF-ARW simulation of potential temperature at 1000 meters, with horizontal wind vectors.  Key features include: enhancement of Sandy&#039;s inner warm-core temperature when passing over the axis of the Gulf Stream; cyclonic encirclement of the cold continental polar air.  Both processes increased the baroclinicity and wind speed surrounding Sandy&#039;s warm inner core and decreased the central pressure preceding landfall.  Color indicates potential temperature in degrees C. Discussed in &lt;a href=&quot;https://ams.confex.com/ams/93Annual/flvgateway.cgi/id/23249?recordingid=23249&quot;&gt;Mel Shapiro&#039;s presentation at the AMS 2013 Townhall&lt;/a&gt; &quot;A research-community perspective of the life cycle of Hurricane Sandy&quot;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
